It is not known how CARGO obtained the software, but it was obtained illegally. Our cyber crimes division suspects an insider attack, which means a Roadeeze employee collaborated with someone at CARGO to give them the software.

We are consulting with San Francisco Police to investigate.

DATES: The crime most likely occured between the dates of Monday, May 4, 2020 and today, Friday, May 8, 2020

MOTIVE: The software in question, roadnav.exe, is extremely valuable. CARGO stands to make a substantial profit while Roadeez may never recover financially.

1. Michelle - CEO
2. Daryl - Lead Software Engineer
3. Xin - Software Engineer Intern
4. Ivan - System Administrator
5. Anna - Administrative Assistant

EVIDENCE: We have obtained a collection of electronic documents from Roadeez. These documents include files from every employee's personal computer, as well as network logs from a company server and calendar entries for the week in question. {'_id': {'$oid': '5f109cbf6e8bb4f66633b23c'}, 'Body': "TECH WATCH

Located in Boston, Roadeez is making waves in the startup scene with its innovative new self-driving car tech. The comapny is small, only five employees, but they don't make the cars; they make the software!

The company is helmed by tech newcomer, Michelle, with her long time friend and Stanford alum, Daryl, as lead developer.

Rumors abound that the company has failed to raise the venture capital it needs, but based on the incredible demo they gave of their software last month, that shouldn't be a problem for long! Larger self-driving car companies like CARGO in San Francisco and Karikampani in the country of Tilapia will certainly be taking note of this rising star.", 'Destination': '', 'Discovered': 'False', 'Document Source': 'Web', 'Document Type': 'Information', 'End Time': 2147483647, 'Importance': 0, 'Keyword': 'roadeez Michelle Daryl CARGO Boston Tech Watch car self driving stanford venture capital karikampani tilapia san francisco', 'Name': 'roadeez_info.html', 'Origin': '', 'Person': 'Michelle Anna Darly Xin Ivan', 'Receiver': '', 'Sender': '', 'Start Time': 1588564800, 'Title': 'Roadeeze: The Next Big Thing in Self-Driving Cars'}

{'_id': {'$oid': '5f109cbf6e8bb4f66633b240'}, 'Body': "FORTUNE MAGAZINE

We sat down with Michelle, founder and CEO of a new, small self-driving car company call Roadeez. Here's what she had to say!

US: How can you develop self-driving cars with such a small team?
MICHELLE: Well, actually, we just develop the software. Our top secret, proprietary navigation algorithms are the absolute best in the business.

US: What experience do you have with tech startups?
MICHELLE: This is my first tech company, but not my first startup. My friend Daryl is our lead developer, so he handles everything related to the software.

US: What's your management philosophy?
MICHELLE: I try not to micro-manage. Daryl knows everything he needs to make great software, so I just try to stay out of his way and raise the money the company needs to make payroll.

US: Is it true you didn't raise as much venture capital as you wanted in this last round?
